> >before you go in. find out the invoice prices of the car, add a reasonable > >profit for the dealer ($200-$300??), offer them that price and stick to > >it.
> > whoa! watch your terminology. "dealer invoice" is *not* "dealer cost".
> ... that's probably true but it's the closest to it that you're going to get. the actual dealer cost depends on a lot of things and even the dealer probably doesn't know exactly what it will be until all the factory kick-backs, incentives, etc. are paid and that often depends on his volume at the end of the month/quarter/whatever. it might be a funny munber but it's all you have to start with, except the sticker, and anyone who pays sticker price is really being ripped off. mark